extracted_characteristics.dt_services:
The Digital Twin supplies a suite of services for operators and developers:
(1) Monitoring – continuous, real‑time acquisition of device state data through IoT‑enabled sensors and real‑time data exchange layers;
(2) Control – execution of control logic defined by Building Control Engineers within the twin to actuate building devices;
(3) Optimization – algorithmic analysis of aggregated data to recommend energy‑saving schedules and operational improvements;
(4) Prediction – predictive analytics that forecast equipment failures and environmental conditions;
(5) Visualization – immersive, interactive interfaces that display the building’s physical and digital states, allowing Facility Managers to interact with and operate the twin.
Custom services can be added by DT Engineers via the modular extension points of the framework.

extracted_characteristics.tooling_and_enablers:
Implementation relies on a model‑driven engineering (MDE) framework that extracts structured representations from BIM models enriched with device definitions, automatically generating deployable Digital Twin artifacts. Core tools include:
• Building Information Modeling (BIM) for static geometry and lifecycle data;
• MDE principles for model transformation and generation;
• Real‑time data exchange middleware that synchronises data streams between sensors/actuators and the twin;
• Interactive visualization platforms for immersive monitoring and control;
• Modular architecture with standardized extension points to plug in custom services, analytics, and simulation engines.
The approach is validated and supported by the TwinLight and BOREALIS research projects.
